  <body>
  <p>Extend a class method with the very cool JavaScript "prototype" object. Read more about JavaScript's prototype object in Elequent JavaScript, Chapter 6, "The Secret Life of Objects". <br>
    <i>To see the JavaScript, open dev tools (SHIFT+CTRL+I) and click on the HTML file under the "Sources" tab. Click on the "Console" tab to see the console output.  </p>
    <script>
    function Explorer(name, discovery) {
          this.name = name;
          this.discovery = discovery;
      }
      Explorer.prototype.sayName = function() {
          console.log("Hi my name is " + this.name);
      };
      
      // define a Leif class
      function Leif(name) {
          this.name = name;
          this.discovery = discovery;
      }
      
      // oops I want Leif to ALSO use the sayName method like all the other Explorers...
      Leif.prototype = new Explorer();
      
      var leif = new Explorer("Leif");
      leif.sayName();
    </script>
  </body>
</html
